"   </div>",
"   <div id=\"basicsTopicLeft\">",
"    <div id=\"topicTitle\">",
"     Patient information: Scleroderma (The Basics)",
"    </div>",
"    <span class=\"view\">",
"     View in",
"     <a class=\"lang\" href=\"./es-419/scleroderma-the-basics?source=topic_page\">",
"      Spanish",
"     </a>",
"    </span>",
"    <a class=\"contributor contributor_credentials\" href=\"./authors-and-editors/patient-information\">",
"     Written by the doctors and editors at UpToDate",
"    </a>",
"    <div id=\"topicText\">",
"     <p class=\"headingAnchor\" id=\"H110678437\">",
"      <span class=\"h1\">",
"       What is scleroderma?",
"      </span>",
"      &nbsp;&mdash;&nbsp;Scleroderma means &ldquo;hard skin.&rdquo; Doctors use the term scleroderma for conditions that affect the skin and tissues that support the organs inside your body. This tissue is called &ldquo;connective tissue.&rdquo;",
"     </p>",
"     <p>",
"      There are 2 main types of scleroderma. &ldquo;Localized&rdquo; scleroderma affects the skin and tissue just under the skin. &ldquo;Systemic&rdquo; scleroderma can affect the skin and organs inside your body, including the heart, lungs, kidneys, and the digestive system. The digestive system includes all the structures and organs that handle and process food, such as the stomach and intestines.",
"     </p>",
"     <p class=\"headingAnchor\" id=\"H110678452\">",
"      <span class=\"h1\">",
"       What are the symptoms of scleroderma?",
"      </span>",
"      &nbsp;&mdash;&nbsp;The most common symptoms of localized scleroderma include:",
"     </p>",
"     <p>",
"      <ul class=\"bulletCompact-block\">",
"       <li>",
"        Streaks or bands of hard, waxy skin on an arm, leg, or the face",
"       </li>",
"       <li>",
"        Patches of hard, dry, smooth skin, usually on the belly, chest, and back",
"       </li>",
"      </ul>",
"     </p>",
"     <p>",
"      The affected areas can be itchy or painful.",
"     </p>",
"     <p>",
"      The symptoms of systemic scleroderma include:",
"     </p>",
"     <p>",
"      <ul class=\"bullet-block\">",
"       <li>",
"        A condition called &ldquo;Raynaud phenomenon&rdquo; that causes the fingers and toes to turn white or purple-blue in response to cold or stress",
"       </li>",
"       <li>",
"        Puffy skin that slowly becomes hard and thicker than normal",
"       </li>",
"       <li>",
"        Joints that become stiff, because the skin around them isn&rsquo;t able to stretch as well as it used to",
"       </li>",
"       <li>",
"        Small white lumps in or under the skin on the fingers - These are called &ldquo;skin deposits.&rdquo; They contain calcium and might also be called &ldquo;calcinosis.&rdquo;",
"       </li>",
"      </ul>",
"     </p>",
"     <p>",
"      Less common symptoms that can happen when other organs are affected include:",
"     </p>",
"     <p>",
"      <ul class=\"bullet-block\">",
"       <li>",
"        Acid reflux - This is when the acid that is normally in your stomach backs up into your esophagus, the tube that carries food from your mouth to your stomach.",
"       </li>",
"       <li>",
"        Trouble swallowing",
"       </li>",
"       <li>",
"        Diarrhea",
"       </li>",
"       <li>",
"        Shortness of breath",
"       </li>",
"      </ul>",
"     </p>",
"     <p class=\"headingAnchor\" id=\"H110678467\">",
"      <span class=\"h1\">",
"       Are there tests for scleroderma?",
"      </span>",
"      &nbsp;&mdash;&nbsp;Yes. Your doctor or nurse might be able to tell if you have it by learning about your symptoms and doing an exam. But you might need other tests, including:",
"     </p>",
"     <p>",
"      <ul class=\"bullet-block\">",
"       <li>",
"        Blood tests",
"       </li>",
"       <li>",
"        Skin biopsy &ndash; For this test, a doctor takes a small sample of your skin. Another doctor then looks at the skin cells under a microscope to check for signs of scleroderma.",
"       </li>",
"      </ul>",
"     </p>",
"     <p class=\"headingAnchor\" id=\"H110678482\">",
"      <span class=\"h1\">",
"       How is scleroderma treated?",
"      </span>",
"      &nbsp;&mdash;&nbsp;The treatment depends on the type of scleroderma you have and your symptoms.",
"     </p>",
"     <p>",
"      Treatments for localized scleroderma include:",
"     </p>",
"     <p>",
"      <ul class=\"bullet-block\">",
"       <li>",
"        Light therapy &ndash; For this treatment, doctors use a machine that gives off a special type of light. They point the light at the affected part of your body.",
"       </li>",
"       <li>",
"        Medicines &ndash; These include prescription skin creams and pills.",
"       </li>",
"      </ul>",
"     </p>",
"     <p>",
"      Treatments for systemic sclerosis include:",
"     </p>",
"     <p>",
"      <ul class=\"bullet-block\">",
"       <li>",
"        Tests every few weeks or months to check your blood pressure and check how well your kidneys and lungs are working",
"       </li>",
"       <li>",
"        Prescription medicines to treat symptoms in different parts of the body",
"       </li>",
"       <li>",
"        Surgery to remove calcinosis",
"       </li>",
"      </ul>",
"     </p>",
"     <p class=\"headingAnchor\" id=\"H110678497\">",
"      <span class=\"h1\">",
"       Is there anything I can do on my own to feel better?",
"      </span>",
"      &nbsp;&mdash;&nbsp;Yes. You can use special creams with &ldquo;lanolin&rdquo; (a greasy substance found in wool) to help keep your skin soft. If itching is a problem, you can take over-the-counter antihistamines, such as",
"      <a class=\"drug drug_patient\" href=\"UTD.htm?24/60/25537?source=see_link\">",
"       diphenhydramine",
"      </a>",
"      (sample brand name: Benadryl&reg;).",
"     </p>",
"     <p class=\"headingAnchor\" id=\"H110678512\">",
"      <span class=\"h1\">",
"       What if I want to get pregnant?",
"      </span>",
"      &nbsp;&mdash;&nbsp;If you have scleroderma, you might have a harder time getting pregnant than women without the disease. You also might be more likely to have a miscarriage (this is when a pregnancy ends before a woman has been pregnant for 20 weeks).",
"     </p>",
"     <p>",
"      During pregnancy, some of your symptoms (such as Raynaud phenomenon) might get better. But other symptoms (such as heartburn) might get worse. If you have kidney problems caused by scleroderma, pregnancy can be very dangerous and even life threatening.",
"     </p>",
"     <p class=\"headingAnchor\" id=\"H110678527\">",
"      <span class=\"h1\">",
"       What will my life be like?",
"      </span>",
"      &nbsp;&mdash;&nbsp;Because scleroderma affects the way you look and, in some cases, your ability to do everyday things, the disease can cause stress and worry. Your doctor can refer you to a counselor or a local scleroderma support group for advice on coping with the condition.",
"     </p>",
"    </div>",
